{
  "local_port": 44402,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where do I start when looking for colleges?",
  "response": "Starting your college search can be an overwhelming process, but breaking it down into steps can help. Here\u2019s a guide to get you started:\n\n1. **Self-Assessment:**\n   - **Interests and Strengths:** Consider your academic interests, potential career paths, and personal values. What subjects excite you? What extracurricular activities do you enjoy?\n   - **Goals:** Determine what you want from your college experience (e.g., small vs. large campus, urban vs. rural setting, etc.).\n\n2. **Research Colleges:**\n   - **Types of Institutions:** Familiarize yourself with different types of colleges (e.g., community colleges, liberal arts colleges, research universities).\n   - **Programs Offered:** Look for colleges that offer strong programs in your areas of interest.\n   - **Accreditation:** Ensure the colleges you consider are accredited by a recognized agency.\n\n3. **Consider Location:**\n   - Think about whether you want to stay close to home or go farther away. Consider climate, urban vs. rural settings, and proximity to family and friends.\n\n4. **Admission Requirements:**\n   - Review the admission requirements for various colleges. Check GPA, standardized test scores (SAT/ACT), application essays, and recommendation letters.\n\n5. **Cost and Financial Aid:**\n   - Research tuition costs and explore financial aid options, scholarships, grants, and loans. Use net price calculators on college websites to estimate your costs.\n\n6. **Visit Campuses:**\n   - If possible, visit colleges to get a feel for the campus culture, meet students and faculty, and attend information sessions. Virtual tours are a good alternative if in-person visits aren\u2019t possible.\n\n7. **Create a List:**\n   - Based on your research and visits, create a list of colleges that meet your criteria. Categorize them into safety schools, target schools, and reach schools.\n\n8. **Application Strategy:**\n   - Determine which application method suits you best (early decision, early action, regular admission).\n   - Start working on your applications, including essays and gathering documents.\n\n9. **Stay Organized:**\n   - Keep track of deadlines, requirements, and documents for each college. Use a spreadsheet or planner to manage your application process.\n\n10. **Seek Guidance:**\n    - Talk to school counselors, teachers, family, and friends. Consider reaching out to current students or alumni for insights.\n\nTaking these steps will help you navigate the college search process more effectively. Remember to give yourself plenty of time to explore your options and make informed decisions!",
